========================================
APACHE CASSANDRA – SYSTEM DESIGN NOTES
========================================

🔹 What is Cassandra?
- Distributed NoSQL (wide-column) database
- Masterless (peer-to-peer architecture)
- Designed for:
  - High scalability
  - High availability
  - No single point of failure
- Inspired by:
  - Amazon Dynamo (distribution)
  - Google Bigtable (data model)

Key Traits:
- Eventually consistent (tunable consistency)
- Write-optimized system
- Handles massive data (TBs–PBs)

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 Data Model (Query-Driven)

Keyspace:
- Like a database
- Defines replication strategy

Table:
- Collection of rows (distributed)

Primary Key:
- Partition Key + Clustering Columns

Partition Key:
- Determines data placement (critical for scaling)

Clustering Columns:
- Define sorting within partition

Wide-Column Model:
- Flexible schema (rows can differ)

Important:
- No joins
- No foreign keys
- No cross-partition queries
- Design based on access patterns

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 Scalability

- Horizontal scaling (add nodes → more capacity)
- Linear scalability

Core Concepts:
- Consistent Hashing → distributes data
- Token Ring → each node owns a range

Advantages:
- No central bottleneck
- Uses commodity hardware

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 High Availability & Fault Tolerance

- Masterless → any node handles requests
- Replication Factor (RF) → multiple copies

Failure Handling:
- Other replicas serve data
- Hinted handoff + repair mechanisms

Result:
- Always available system

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 CAP Theorem

C → Consistency
A → Availability
P → Partition Tolerance

Cassandra:
- AP system (Availability + Partition tolerance)
- Uses tunable consistency

Consistency Levels:
- ONE → fastest, less consistent
- QUORUM → balanced
- ALL → strongest, slowest

Trade-off:
- Higher consistency = higher latency

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 Write Path (Very Important ⭐)

Flow:
Write Request
   ↓
Commit Log (durability)
   ↓
Memtable (in-memory)
   ↓
SSTable (disk, immutable)

Key Points:
- Sequential writes → very fast
- No random disk I/O
- Based on LSM-tree design

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 Read Path

Flow:
- Check Memtable
- Check Cache
- Read SSTables
- Merge results

Optimizations:
- Bloom Filters → avoid disk reads
- Partition Index → faster lookup

Trade-off:
- Reads slower than writes (merge cost)

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 Denormalization

Rule:
- Design for queries, NOT normalization

Why:
- No joins supported
- Distributed joins are expensive

Approach:
- Duplicate data across tables

Example:
- orders_by_user
- orders_by_date
- orders_by_status

Pros:
- Fast reads

Cons:
- Data duplication
- More storage usage

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 When to Use Cassandra

Best For:
- Large-scale systems (TBs/PBs)
- Write-heavy workloads
- Time-series data (logs, metrics)
- Distributed/global applications

Examples:
- Messaging systems
- Activity feeds
- IoT data ingestion

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 When NOT to Use

- Complex joins required
- Strong ACID transactions needed
- Small-scale applications

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 Real-World Usage (Patterns)

- Social media feeds
- Streaming platforms
- Ride-sharing systems
- Event logging pipelines
- Telecom + IoT systems

--------------------------------------------------

🔹 Key Interview Points

- Masterless distributed DB
- AP system with tunable consistency
- Write-optimized (Commit Log + Memtable + SSTable)
- Query-based data modeling
- Denormalization is required
- Linear scalability via consistent hashing

--------------------------------------------------

🧠 One-liner:
Cassandra is a highly available, distributed NoSQL database optimized for write-heavy workloads and designed around partition keys and access patterns.